-{"id":"git_safety_guard-2fma","title":"[Epic 6] Temporary/Expiring Allowlist Entries","description":"## EPIC 6: Temporary/Expiring Allowlist Entries

### Background & Context
Users frequently need to run a dangerous command once—debugging, cleanup, migration. Currently they either:
1. Fight with dcg repeatedly (frustrating)
2. Permanently allowlist and forget to remove it (security debt)
3. Disable dcg entirely (dangerous)

None of these is acceptable. We need TIME-LIMITED allowlisting.

### Goals & Objectives
1. Extend allowlist config to support expiration (timestamp, TTL, session)
2. Auto-expire entries without manual cleanup
3. CLI shorthand for quick temporary allowlisting
4. Prevent security configuration drift

### Reasoning & Justification
This is ranked #6 because it solves the TEMPORARY EXCEPTION problem:
- Provides escape hatch without permanent security debt
- Self-cleaning configuration
- Matches real-world workflows (one-time migrations, debugging)
- Simple mental model ("allow for 1 hour")

### Config Schema Design

TOML format:
[[allowlist_rules]]
pattern = "rm -rf /tmp/debug-*"
expires = "2024-01-20T00:00:00Z"  # Absolute timestamp

[[allowlist_rules]]
pattern = "docker system prune -af"
ttl = "4h"  # Expires 4 hours after config read

[[allowlist_rules]]
pattern = "DROP DATABASE staging_*"
session = true  # Expires when shell session ends

CLI shorthand:
dcg allow "rm -rf ./vendor" --for 1h
dcg allow "docker system prune" --session
dcg allow "DROP TABLE temp" --until "2024-01-20"

### Implementation Considerations
- Expiration fields in AllowlistRule struct
- During evaluation, check if entry has expired
- Session tracking via env var or PID file
- CLI 'allow' command for quick additions
- 'dcg allowlist list' to show active entries with status
- Consider auto-pruning expired entries vs leaving as documentation

### Session Tracking Options
1. Environment variable (SHELL_SESSION_ID or similar)
2. PID file with parent shell PID
3. TTY identifier
4. Explicit session ID set by user

### Success Criteria
- Temporary allowlists work as expected
- Expired entries are correctly rejected
- CLI shorthand is intuitive
- Session-scoped allowlists work across shell commands
- No stale entries accumulate in config

### Related Codebase Files
- src/config.rs (expiration fields, parsing)
- src/evaluator.rs (expiration checking)
- src/cli.rs (allow subcommand)

### Dependencies
- Builds on Epic 5 (uses extended allowlist schema)

### Project Goal Alignment
This serves 'ergonomic, reliable' goals. Temporary exceptions are a real need; providing a proper mechanism prevents workarounds that compromise security.","status":"in_progress","priority":2,"issue_type":"epic","owner":"jeff141421@gmail.com","created_at":"2026-01-18T18:09:34.897969712Z","created_by":"Dicklesworthstone","updated_at":"2026-04-28T05:36:37.322787266Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"labels":["core","normalization","security"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"git_safety_guard-2fma","depends_on_id":"git_safety_guard-nuyf","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-01-18T19:14:46.282169820Z","created_by":"Dicklesworthstone","metadata":"","thread_id":""}]}
